 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aeloryn>Aeloryn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(12/30/02 1:13:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=763.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cheatch Learn to run a raid.</span><hr size=1> I can understand why any melee class jumped on Tena for his post. I have a few RL friends who play paladins and I've listened to them complain about their epic books for the last couple years (literally).<br>
<br>
However, the raid leader DOES deserve to get flamed for what happened. A pick up raid is all about the loot. This isn't a guild function or even a regular open raid. A lot of people in particular classes (such as clerics and enchanters) are pestered with tells to beg them to come to these things. So, common courtesy is for the loot system to be up front and clear. The screw up here happened before Nagafen died. Open rolls on items should mean that you get everyone to register in advance what item they want to roll on in the event that item is dropped. That way casters go for the caster gear or maybe they go after a rich money item like a CoF. At the very least there should be no surprises that someone who is NOT a paladin wants to roll on the book. Then the raid leader can either say: &quot;Ok, you're down for the book roll&quot; OR &quot;Sorry, pallies only, pick another item.&quot; But you don't have a situation where the dragon drops, and everyone believes they are entitled to roll on one of the items on the corpse.<br>
<br>
If all the details are true as presented, Cheatch essentially scammed a bunch of people into showing up at this raid. I don't feel a whole lot of sympathy because it's a useful lesson to all that these raids are mostly a waste of time particularly if you don't know the references of the raid leader. Cheatch though deserves a public drubbing for how he did this.<br>
<br>
As for everyone that jumped on Tena, I think you should give some thought as to whether you really stand behind someone running a raid like this. I've run across a bunch of you in game and I don't think that any of you would agree with a raid leader pulling a bait n switch. Tena was in poor taste asking for roll on an epic book -- even for MQ -- but the real issue was the raid rules and how they were poorly handled from the beginning.<br>
